bug.short_desc: [compiler] detection of name clash depends on order of super interfaces

long_desc.thetext: Srikanth, do you have a comment? I think you were last to touch this test case on behalf of bug 354229.

(In reply to comment #1) > Srikanth, do you have a comment? > I think you were last to touch this test case on behalf of bug 354229.
No, I have only a vague memory of having observed such behavior with javac actually. Don't remember if these were of recent vintage though

I noticed while debugging that org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.lookup.MethodVerifier15.computeSubstituteMethod(MethodBinding, MethodBinding) carries a comment:
// TODO (kent) another place where we expect the superinterfaces to be in the exact same order

(In reply to comment #3) > I noticed while debugging that > org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.lookup.MethodVerifier15. > computeSubstituteMethod(MethodBinding, MethodBinding) carries a comment: > > > // TODO (kent) another place where we expect the superinterfaces to be in > the exact same order
oops, thanks for digging this out.

(In reply to comment #4) > (In reply to comment #3) > > I noticed while debugging that > > org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.lookup.MethodVerifier15. > > computeSubstituteMethod(MethodBinding, MethodBinding) carries a comment: > > > > > > // TODO (kent) another place where we expect the superinterfaces to be in > > the exact same order > > oops, thanks for digging this out.
Sounded like a hot trace, but looking at the source code I see two arrays being compared in nested loops, i.e., comparing each element of array 1 inside against all elements of array 2 (until found). Doesn't look like a order-sensitive thing to me.

As this is blocking bug 388739 I'm currently investigating.
My current thinking being: the mentioned name clash error is wrong in both cases (classes X and Y) because this kind of error doesn't apply if both methods are abstract (see JLS 8.4.8.4).
The bogus asymmetry stems from one check in MethodVerifier15.checkMethods that only tests one direction where it probably should test both directions: isSubstituteParameterSubsignature(inheritedMethod, otherInheritedMethod)
After fixing the asymmetry, 7 tests in MethodVerifyTests fail - investigating.

Created attachment 222262 patch under test
Here's a patch under test, containing these changes: - in two cases method compatibility must be checked in both directions - when checking inherited methods skip those that are already known to be overridden by a current method - allow skipping also if one super-interface method replaces another method from its transitive super-interface Also adjusted some expected test results. (change in MethodVerifyTest.testBug317719f() is due to accidental interaction with the change from bug 317719 (mimic javac6 bug)).

Srikanth, this patch touches some delicate aspects of the method verifier, so I'd prefer if you could review the changes both in the code and in tests.
The initial motivation to making these changes is as a necessary foundation for pending work in bug 388739.
Reverting any of the code changes should trigger a specific failure in MethodVerifyTest. The currently running tests identified one more test needing adjustment: GenericTypeTest.test1239() will list one fewer method in one of its error messages.
Let me know if you want me to push it to gerrit so you can more easily give detailed comments.
Note, that the current patch is based on BETA_JAVA8, but it does not need any Java8 stuff, so we *might* also think of porting it into master, too, if all is well.

Created attachment 222263 updated patch
Patch with one more test adjustment (already mentioned in comment 8)
With this patch all JDT/Core tests are happy.
